2. Proposal checklist — Activity A

Section 1: Business context

Check	Exactly what to write
☐	Explain who Greenfield Local Hub (GLH) are. Say they are a cooperative of local farmers and food producers.  ￼
☐	Explain what GLH already offers: a retail outlet, collective marketing, product management, stock control, and traceability.  ￼
☐	Explain why they need a digital solution now.
☐	Explain your proposed solution in one short paragraph, for example: “I am proposing an interactive website/web app for customers and producers.”
☐	Keep this section similar to the distinction example, which introduces the client, what they do, and what the digital solution will achieve.  ￼

Section 2: Empathy map

Check	Exactly what to write
☐	Create an empathy map for at least the main users, such as customer and producer.
☐	Include headings like Says, Thinks, Does, Feels.
☐	Base it on realistic needs, such as wanting easy ordering, clear stock, quick delivery options, and simple navigation.
☐	This is not directly listed in the brief, but the distinction example uses it and it makes the proposal stronger.

Section 3: User stories and acceptance criteria

Check	Exactly what to write
☐	Write user stories in the format As a… I want… so that…
☐	Do this for key users such as customer, producer, and possibly GLH admin.
☐	Add acceptance criteria after each story saying exactly what the system must do.
☐	Use the distinction example as a model because it does this clearly.

Good user stories to include:
	•	As a customer, I want to browse products by category so that I can find items quickly.
	•	As a customer, I want to place an order for collection or delivery so that I can choose the most convenient option.
	•	As a customer, I want to view my order history so that I can check previous purchases.
	•	As a producer, I want to update stock levels so that customers only see what is available.
	•	As a producer, I want to update product details so that product information stays accurate.
	•	As a producer, I want to view incoming orders so that I can prepare them on time.

Section 4: Functional requirements

Check	Exactly what to write
☐	Make a section called Functional Requirements because the brief specifically asks for it.  ￼
☐	Break it into pages or features, just like the distinction example does.
☐	For each feature, explain what the system shows, what the user can do, what data is entered, and what happens after the user submits something.

Best headings to use:
	•	Homepage
	•	Producers page
	•	Product catalogue
	•	Product details page
	•	Basket / checkout
	•	Delivery or collection booking
	•	Customer account
	•	Order history
	•	Producer dashboard
	•	Stock management
	•	Loyalty scheme
	•	Order tracking

Section 5: Non-functional requirements

Check	Exactly what to write
☐	Make a section called Non-functional Requirements.  ￼
☐	Include headings such as Security, Performance, Maintainability, Usability, Accessibility, Reliability.
☐	Write clear statements like “The system must validate all user input” or “The website should load quickly on mobile devices.”
☐	The distinction example includes security, maintainability, performance and accessibility, so that is a good model.

Section 6: Decomposition

Check	Exactly what to write
☐	Add a section called Decomposition because the brief asks for it.  ￼
☐	Break the full system into smaller parts.
☐	Explain the smaller problems that must be solved for each part.
☐	Follow the distinction example structure here.

Good parts to decompose:
	•	user registration and login
	•	browsing products
	•	searching and filtering
	•	managing basket
	•	placing an order
	•	choosing collection or delivery
	•	updating stock
	•	managing product details
	•	loyalty rewards
	•	tracking orders

Section 7: KPIs and user acceptance criteria

Check	Exactly what to write
☐	Add a KPIs section because the brief asks for this.  ￼
☐	Split KPIs into business KPIs and website/system KPIs, like the distinction example.
☐	Make each KPI measurable.
☐	Add a separate User Acceptance Criteria section saying what must be true for users to accept the final solution.

Good GLH KPIs:
	•	number of completed orders per week
	•	repeat customer rate
	•	average order value
	•	number of producers actively using the dashboard
	•	product page conversion rate
	•	page load time
	•	basket abandonment rate
	•	percentage of successful deliveries or collections

Good user acceptance criteria:
	•	users can find products in a small number of clicks
	•	customers can place an order without confusion
	•	producers can update stock without technical help
	•	users can access the site on mobile
	•	order history is visible in accounts
	•	accessibility features work correctly

Section 8: Description of proposed solution

Check	Exactly what to write
☐	Add a section called Description of Proposed Solution.
☐	Summarise the whole system in a clear paragraph or two.
☐	Mention the main features and the benefits for GLH and the users.
☐	Use the distinction example’s summary style as inspiration.

Section 9: Justification

Check	Exactly what to write
☐	Add a section called Justification.
☐	Explain exactly how your solution meets the needs of the client and the users.
☐	Link each main feature back to a specific need from the brief.
☐	The distinction example does this by taking each client need and explaining how the feature solves it.

Section 10: Risks and mitigation

Check	Exactly what to write
☐	Add a section called How potential risks will be mitigated because the brief specifically asks for this.  ￼
☐	Identify realistic risks for your solution.
☐	Explain how each risk will be reduced.
☐	The distinction example includes risk sections like poor data quality, data loss, and data breaches.

Good risks for GLH:
